# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alistipes
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alistipes/alistipes-communis] A 2024 study investigated changes to human gut microbiome in relation to intense effort exercise and found *A. communis* to be abundant in individuals undertaking strength training during the Wingate test (a test involving resistance cycling).
[src:alistipes/alistipes-communis] In 2026 a study from the Northeast Agricultural University in Harbin, China, conducted the first study of how *A. communis* mechanically contributed to its host.
[src:alistipes/alistipes-communis] Sixty-six chicks were involved in a study investigating *A. communis* and the regulation of abdominal fat percentage (AFD).
[src:alistipes/alistipes-communis] When *A. communis* was introduced to the cecum (a pouch found at the start of the large intestine) of the chickens it caused shifts in the microbial cecum biome.
[src:alistipes/alistipes-communis] *A. communis* was found to be involved in the metabolism of amino acid, galactose, vitamins, amino/nucleotide sugars and carbon.
[src:alistipes/alistipes-communis] It was a key microbial species in regulating AFD in chickens, associated with an increase in the AFD, due to enhanced amino acid and carbohydrate metabolism.
[src:alistipes/alistipes-onderdonkii] This species was named after microbiologist Andrew.
[src:alistipes/alistipes-onderdonkii] B Onderdonk to pay homage to his contribution to intestinal microbiota and anaerobic bacteria.
[src:alistipes/alistipes-onderdonkii] In 2020 it was split into two sub species *A. onderdonkii* subsp. vulgaris and *A. onderdonkii* subsp.
[src:alistipes/alistipes-onderdonkii] Records of *A. onderdonkii* causing infection in humans is very rare, with the first report occurring in 2006.
[src:alistipes/alistipes-onderdonkii] The first confirmed case by 16S RNA analysis was in February 2020 where a severe infection was caused in a 58 year old man.
[src:alistipes/alistipes-onderdonkii] Resistance to the antibiotics penicillin and moxifloxacin was noted in this case, but was successfully treated with meropenem, metronidazole and surgery.
[src:alistipes/alistipes-onderdonkii] In a study on mice and *A. onderonkii* has been shown to be able to reduce tumour necrosis factor production, which in excessive amounts can cause damage to skin grafts, and therefore suggesting this species could be beneficial for skin graft survival.
[src:alistipes/alistipes-onderdonkii] The ability of *A. onderonkii* as a protective agent in radiotherapy treatment has been investigated.
[src:alistipes/alistipes-onderdonkii] After radiation exposure to the intestines of mice, the administration of *A. onderdonkii* reduced intestinal damage and significantly improved survival.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] An **anaerobic organism** or **anaerobe** is any organism that does not require molecular oxygen for its growth.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] It may react negatively or even die in the presence of free oxygen.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] Anaerobic organisms do not use oxygen as a terminal electron acceptor in their respiration process to produce energy, but a less powerful oxidizing agent, such as nitrate, ferric ion, Mn(IV), sulfate or bicarbonate anions.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] In contrast, an aerobic organism (aerobe) is an organism that requires a sufficiently oxygenated environment to respire, produce its energy, and thrive.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] However, a minuscule multicellular organism, with an exceptionally rare metabolism and surviving in a hypersaline brine pool in the darkness of the bottom of the Mediterranean Sea, has been recently discovered.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] Meanwhile, it remains a scientific curiosity, as the much higher energy requirements of most multicellular organisms cannot be met by anaerobic respiration.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] The deep seafloor and its underlying unconsolidated sediments ranks among the largest potential habitats for anaerobic microorganisms on Earth.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] Moreover, chemoautotroph microbes also thrive around hydrothermal vents, discharging hot water on the ocean seabed near mid-ocean ridges, where anaerobic conditions prevail.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] These microbes produce energy in the absence of sunlight or oxygen through a process called anaerobic respiration, whereby inorganic compounds and ions such as protons (H+), elemental sulfur and its derivatives (SO2−4, S2O2−3), or ferric ions, are reduced to drive oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] In his 14 June 1680 letter to the Royal Society, Antonie van Leeuwenhoek described an experiment he carried out by filling two identical glass tubes about halfway with crushed pepper powder, to which some clean rain water was added.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] Van Leeuwenhoek sealed one of the glass tubes with a flame and left the other open.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] In 1913, Martinus Beijerinck repeated Van Leeuwenhoek's experiment and identified *Clostridium butyricum* as a prominent anaerobic bacterium in the sealed pepper infusion tube liquid.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] Some obligate anaerobes use fermentation, while others use anaerobic respiration.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] Aerotolerant organisms are strictly fermentative.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] In the presence of oxygen, facultative anaerobes use aerobic respiration.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] In the absence of oxygen, some facultative anaerobes use fermentation, while others may use anaerobic respiration.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] There are many anaerobic fermentative reactions.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] The energy released in this reaction (without ADP and phosphate) is approximately 150 kJ per mol, which is conserved in generating two ATP from ADP per glucose.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] This is only 5% of the energy per sugar molecule that the typical aerobic reaction generates.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] The energy released is about 180 kJ/mol, which is conserved when 2 ATP are generated from 2 ADP per glucose.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] Anaerobic bacteria and archaea use these and many other fermentative pathways, e.g., propionic acid fermentation, butyric acid fermentation, solvent fermentation, mixed acid fermentation, butanediol fermentation, Stickland fermentation, acetogenesis, or methanogenesis.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] Creatine, an organic compound found in animals, provides a way for ATP to be utilized in the muscle.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] The phosphorylation of creatine allows for the storage of readily available phosphate that can be supplied to the muscles.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] The reaction is reversible as well, allowing cellular ATP levels to be maintained during anoxic conditions.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] This process in animals is seen to be coupled with metabolic suppression to allow certain fish, such as goldfish, to survive environmental anoxic conditions for a short period.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] Since normal microbial culturing is done in atmospheric air, which contains molecular oxygen, culturing anaerobes requires special techniques.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] The Gas-pak System is an isolated container that achieves an anaerobic environment by the reaction of water with sodium borohydride and sodium bicarbonate tablets, which produce hydrogen gas and carbon dioxide.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] Hydrogen then reacts with oxygen gas on a palladium catalyst to produce more water, thereby removing oxygen gas.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] The issue with the Gas-Pak method is that an adverse reaction can occur, leading to bacterial death; therefore, a thioglycolate medium should be used.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] The thioglycolate supplies a medium mimicking that of a dicot plant, thus providing not only an anaerobic environment but all the nutrients needed for the bacteria to multiply.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] On May the 6 2018, a French team evidenced a link between redox and gut anaerobes based on clinical studies of severe acute malnutrition.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] These findings led to the development of an aerobic culture of "anaerobes" by the addition of antioxidants in the culture medium.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] Very few multicellular life forms are anaerobic, since only aerobic respiration can provide enough energy for a complex metabolism.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] Exceptions include three species of *Loricifera* (< 1 mm in size) and the 10-cell *Henneguya zschokkei*.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] In 2010, three species of anaerobic *Loricifera* were discovered in the hypersaline anoxic L'Atalante basin at the bottom of the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] They lack mitochondria, which contain the oxidative phosphorylation pathway, which in all other animals combines oxygen with glucose to produce metabolic energy; thus, they consume no oxygen.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] Instead, these *loricifera* derive their energy from hydrogen, using hydrogenosomes.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] Anaerobic respiration and its end products can facilitate symbiosis between anaerobes and aerobes.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] This occurs across taxa, often in compensation for nutritional needs.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] Anaerobiosis and symbiosis are found in interactions between ciliates and prokaryotes.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] Anaerobic ciliates interact with prokaryotes in an endosymbiotic relationship.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] These relationships are mediated in which the ciliate leaves end products that its prokaryotic symbiont utilizes.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] The ciliate achieves this through fermentative metabolism.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] The rumen of various animals houses this ciliate alongside many other anaerobic bacteria, protozoans, and fungi.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] In specific, methanogenic archaea found in the rumen acts as a symbiont to anaerobic ciliates.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] These anaerobes are useful to those with a rumen due to their ability to break down cellulose, making it bioavailable when otherwise indigestible by animals.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] Termites utilize anaerobic bacteria to fix and recapture nitrogen.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] Specifically, the termite's hindgut is full of nitrogen-fixing bacteria, whose functions depend on the nitrogen concentration of the diet.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] Acetylene reduction in termites was observed to upregulate in termites with nitrogen-poor diets, meaning that nitrogenase activity rose as the nitrogen content of the termite was reduced.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] One of the functions of termite microbiota is to recapture nitrogen from the termite's uric acid.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] This allows nitrogen conservation from a diet otherwise low in nitrogen.
[src:alistipes/anaerobic-organism] The hindgut microbiome of different termites has been analyzed, showing 16 different anaerobic species of bacteria, including Clostridia, Enterobacteriaceae, and Gram-positive cocci.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] In casual discourse, the words *anxiety* and *fear* are often used interchangeably.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] The umbrella term 'anxiety disorder' refers to a number of specific disorders that include fears (phobias) and/or anxiety symptoms.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] There are several types of anxiety disorders, including generalized anxiety disorder, hypochondriasis, specific phobia, social anxiety disorder, separation anxiety disorder, agoraphobia, panic disorder, and selective mutism.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Individual disorders can be diagnosed using the specific and unique symptoms, triggering events, and timing.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] A medical professional must evaluate a person before diagnosing them with an anxiety disorder to ensure that their anxiety cannot be attributed to another medical illness or mental disorder.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] It is possible for an individual to have more than one anxiety disorder during their life or to have more than one anxiety disorder at the same time.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Comorbid mental disorders or substance use disorders are common in those with anxiety.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Comorbid depression (lifetime prevalence) is seen in 20–70% of those with social anxiety disorder, 50% of those with panic disorder and 43% of those with general anxiety disorder.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] The 12 month prevalence of alcohol or substance use disorders in those with anxiety disorders is 16.5%.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Worldwide, anxiety disorders are the second most common type of mental disorders after *depressive disorders*.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Anxiety disorders affect nearly 30% of adults at some point in their lives, with an estimated 4% of the global population currently experiencing an anxiety disorder.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] However, *anxiety disorders are treatable*, and a number of effective treatments are available.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Most people are able to lead normal, productive lives with some form of treatment.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Generalized anxiety disorder (GAD) is a common disorder characterized by long-lasting anxiety that is not focused on any one object or situation.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Those with generalized anxiety disorder experience non-specific persistent fear and worry and become overly concerned with everyday matters.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Generalized anxiety disorder is "characterized by chronic excessive worry accompanied by three or more of the following symptoms: restlessness, fatigue, concentration problems, irritability, muscle tension, and sleep disturbance".
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Generalized anxiety disorder is the most common anxiety disorder to affect older adults.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Anxiety can be a symptom of a medical or substance use disorder problem, and medical professionals must be aware of this.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] A diagnosis of GAD is made when a person has been excessively worried about an everyday problem for six months or more.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] These stresses can include family life, work, social life, or their own health.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] A person may find that they have problems making daily decisions and remembering commitments as a result of a lack of concentration and/or preoccupation with worry.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] A symptom can be a strained appearance, with increased sweating from the hands, feet, and axillae, along with tearfulness, which can suggest depression.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Before a diagnosis of anxiety disorder is made, physicians must rule out drug-induced anxiety and other medical causes.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] In children, GAD may be associated with headaches, restlessness, abdominal pain, and heart palpitations.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Typically, it begins around eight to nine years of age.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] The largest category of anxiety disorders is that of specific phobias, which includes all cases in which fear and anxiety are triggered by a specific stimulus or situation.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Between 5% and 12% of the population worldwide has specific phobias.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] According to the National Institute of Mental Health, a phobia is an intense fear of or aversion to specific objects or situations.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Individuals with a phobia typically anticipate terrifying consequences from encountering the object of their fear, which can be anything from an animal to a location to a bodily fluid to a particular situation.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Common phobias are flying, blood, water, highway driving, and tunnels.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] When people are exposed to their phobia, they may experience trembling, shortness of breath, or rapid heartbeat.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] People with specific phobias often go to extreme lengths to avoid encountering their phobia.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] People with specific phobias understand that their fear is not proportional to the actual potential danger, but they can still become overwhelmed by it.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] With panic disorder, a person has brief attacks of intense terror and apprehension, often marked by trembling, shaking, confusion, dizziness, or difficulty breathing.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] These panic attacks are defined by the APA as fear or discomfort that abruptly arises and peaks in less than ten minutes but can last for several hours.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Attacks can be triggered by stress, irrational thoughts, general fear, fear of the unknown, or even when engaging in exercise.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] However, sometimes the trigger is unclear, and attacks can arise without warning.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] To help prevent an attack, one can avoid the trigger.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] This can mean avoiding places, people, types of behaviors, or certain situations that have been known to cause a panic attack.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] This being said, not all attacks can be prevented.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] In addition to recurrent and unexpected panic attacks, a diagnosis of panic disorder requires that said attacks have chronic consequences: either worry over the attacks' potential implications, persistent fear of future attacks, or significant changes in behavior related to the attacks.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] As such, those with panic disorder experience symptoms even outside of specific panic episodes.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Often, normal changes in heartbeat are noticed, leading them to think something is wrong with their heart or they are about to have another panic attack.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] In some cases, a heightened awareness (hypervigilance) of body functioning occurs during panic attacks, wherein any perceived physiological change is interpreted as a possible life-threatening illness (i.e., extreme hypochondriasis).
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Panic disorder is commonly comorbid with anxiety due to the consistent fight or flight response that one's brain is being put under at such a high repetitive rate.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Another one of the very big leading causes of someone developing a panic disorder has a lot to do with one's childhood.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] The article provides knowledge on a positive trend in children who experience abuse and have low self-esteem to later on develop disorders such as generalized anxiety disorder and panic disorder.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Agoraphobia is a specific anxiety disorder wherein an individual is afraid of being in a place or situation where escape is difficult or embarrassing or where help may be unavailable.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Agoraphobia is strongly linked with panic disorder and is often precipitated by the fear of having a panic attack.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] A common manifestation involves needing to be in constant view of a door or other escape route.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] In addition to the fears themselves, the term agoraphobia is often used to refer to avoidance behaviors that individuals often develop.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] For example, following a panic attack while driving, someone with agoraphobia may develop anxiety over driving and will therefore avoid driving.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] These avoidance behaviors can have serious consequences and often reinforce the fear they are caused by.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] In a severe case of agoraphobia, the person may never leave their home.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Social anxiety disorder (SAD), also known as social phobia, describes an intense fear and avoidance of negative public scrutiny, public embarrassment, humiliation, or social interaction.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] This fear can be specific to particular social situations (such as public speaking) or it can be experienced in most or all social situations.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Roughly 7% of American adults have social anxiety disorder, and more than 75% of people experience their first symptoms in their childhood or early teenage years.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Social anxiety often manifests specific physical symptoms, including blushing, sweating, rapid heart rate, and difficulty speaking.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] As with all phobic disorders, those with social anxiety often attempt to avoid the source of their anxiety; in the case of social anxiety, this is particularly problematic, and in severe cases, it can lead to complete social isolation.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Children are also affected by social anxiety disorder, although their associated symptoms are different from those of teenagers and adults.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] They may experience difficulty processing or retrieving information, sleep deprivation, disruptive behaviors in class, and irregular class participation.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Social physique anxiety (SPA) is a sub-type of social anxiety involving concern over the evaluation of one's body by others.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] SPA is common among adolescents, especially females.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD) was once an anxiety disorder (now moved to *trauma- and stressor-related disorders* in the DSM-5) that results from a traumatic experience.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] PTSD affects approximately 3.5% of U.S. adults every year, and an estimated one in eleven people will be diagnosed with PTSD in their lifetime.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Post-traumatic stress can result from an extreme situation, such as combat, natural disaster, rape, hostage situations, child abuse, bullying, or even a serious accident.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] It can also result from long-term (chronic) exposure to a severe stressor— for example, soldiers who endure individual battles but cannot cope with continuous combat.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Common symptoms include hypervigilance, flashbacks, avoidant behaviors, anxiety, anger, and depression.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] In addition, individuals may experience sleep disturbances.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] People who have PTSD often try to detach themselves from their friends and family and have difficulty maintaining these close relationships.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] There are a number of treatments that form the basis of the care plan for those with PTSD; such treatments include cognitive behavioral therapy (CBT), prolonged exposure therapy, stress inoculation therapy, medication, psychotherapy, and support from family and friends.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Post-traumatic stress disorder research began with US military veterans of the Vietnam War, as well as natural and non-natural disaster victims.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Studies have found the degree of exposure to a disaster to be the best predictor of PTSD.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Separation anxiety disorder (SepAD) is the feeling of excessive and inappropriate levels of anxiety over being separated from a person or place.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Separation anxiety is a normal part of development in babies or children, and it is only when this feeling is excessive or inappropriate that it can be considered a disorder.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Separation anxiety disorder affects roughly 7% of adults and 4% of children, but childhood cases tend to be more severe; in some instances, even a brief separation can produce panic.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Treating a child earlier may prevent problems.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] This may include training the parents and family on how to deal with it.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Often, the parents will reinforce the anxiety because they do not know how to properly work through it with the child.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] In addition to parent training and family therapy, medication, such as SSRIs, can be used to treat separation anxiety.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Selective mutism (SM) is a disorder in which a person who is normally capable of speech does not speak in specific situations or to specific people.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Selective mutism usually co-exists with shyness or social anxiety.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] People with selective mutism stay silent even when the consequences of their silence include shame, social ostracism, or even punishment.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Selective mutism affects about 0.8% of people at some point in their lives.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Testing for selective mutism is important because doctors must determine if it is an issue associated with the child's hearing or movements associated with the jaw or tongue and if the child can understand when others are speaking to them.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Generally, cognitive behavioral therapy (CBT) is the recommended approach for treating selective mutism, but prospective long-term outcome studies are lacking.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Evolutionary psychiatry interprets anxiety as part of an evolved defensive system calibrated to potential threat.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] According to the "smoke-alarm principle," anxiety mechanisms are expected to err on the side of false alarms because the cost of unnecessary fear is typically lower than the cost of failing to detect genuine danger.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] This framework has been extended to modern settings, where mismatch between ancestral and contemporary threat profiles may contribute to chronic or generalised anxiety.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] The diagnosis of anxiety disorders is made by symptoms, triggers, and an individual's personal and family histories.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] There are no objective biomarkers or laboratory tests that can diagnose anxiety.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] It is important for a medical professional to evaluate a person for other medical and mental causes of prolonged anxiety because treatments will vary considerably.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Numerous questionnaires have been developed for clinical use and can be used for an objective scoring system.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Symptoms may vary between each sub-type of generalized anxiety disorder.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Generally, symptoms must be present for at least six months, occur more days than not, and significantly impair a person's ability to function in daily life.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Symptoms may include feeling nervous, anxious, or on edge, worrying excessively, difficulty concentrating, restlessness, and irritability.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Questionnaires developed for clinical use include the State-Trait Anxiety Inventory (STAI), the Generalized Anxiety Disorder 7 (GAD-7), the Beck Anxiety Inventory (BAI), the Zung Self-Rating Anxiety Scale, and the Taylor Manifest Anxiety Scale.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Other questionnaires combine anxiety and depression measurements, such as the Hamilton Anxiety Rating Scale, the Hospital Anxiety and Depression Scale (HADS), the Patient Health Questionnaire (PHQ), and the Patient-Reported Outcomes Measurement Information System (PROMIS).
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Examples of specific anxiety questionnaires include the Liebowitz Social Anxiety Scale (LSAS), the Social Interaction Anxiety Scale (SIAS), the Social Phobia Inventory (SPIN), the Social Phobia Scale (SPS), and the Social Anxiety Questionnaire (SAQ-A30).
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] The GAD-7 has a sensitivity of 57–94% and a specificity of 82–88% in the diagnosis of general anxiety disorder.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] All screening questionnaires, if positive, should be followed by clinical interview including assessment of impairment and distress, avoidance behaviors, symptom history and persistence to definitively diagnose an anxiety disorder.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Some organizations support routinely screening all adults for anxiety disorders, with the US Preventative Services Task Force recommending screening for all adults younger than 65.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Anxiety disorders differ from developmentally normal fear or anxiety by being excessive or persisting beyond developmentally appropriate periods.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] They differ from transient fear or anxiety, often stress-induced, by being persistent (e.g., typically lasting 6 months or more), although the criterion for duration is intended as a general guide with allowance for some degree of flexibility and is sometimes of shorter duration in children.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] The diagnosis of an anxiety disorder requires first ruling out an underlying medical cause.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Anxiety and panic disorders as well as other neuropsychiatric disorders can be a symptom of mast cell activation syndrome (MCAS).
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Several drugs can also cause or worsen anxiety, whether through intoxication, withdrawal, or chronic use.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] These include alcohol, tobacco, cannabis, sedatives (including prescription benzodiazepines), opioids (including prescription painkillers and illicit drugs like heroin), stimulants (such as caffeine, cocaine, and amphetamines), hallucinogens, and inhalants.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Focus is increasing on the prevention of anxiety disorders.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] There is tentative evidence to support the use of cognitive behavioral therapy and mindfulness therapy.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] A 2013 review found no effective measures to prevent GAD in adults.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] A 2017 review found that psychological and educational interventions had a small benefit for the prevention of anxiety.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Research indicates that predictors of the emergence of anxiety disorders partly differ from the factors that predict their persistence.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] A big factor that goes into anxiety disorder prevention starts in childhood.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Based on the cited article, parents have a big part in whether or not their child will develop anxiety in their future.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Specific interventions have been tested to educate parents with young children on how to care and prevent a disorder like anxiety from becoming a bigger issue in their child's teen to adult life.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] The study also shared that since it is such a new intervention that there is not much information on long term results, however it does seem to be looking in a positive direction.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Treatment options include psychotherapy, medications and lifestyle changes.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] There is no clear evidence as to whether psychotherapy or medication is more effective; the specific medication decision can be made by a doctor and patient with consideration for the patient's specific circumstances and symptoms.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] If, while on treatment with a chosen medication, the person's anxiety does not improve, another medication may be offered.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Specific treatments will vary by sub-type of anxiety disorder, a person's other medical conditions, and medications.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Cognitive behavioral therapy (CBT) is effective for anxiety disorders and is a first-line treatment.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] CBT is the most widely studied and preferred form of psychotherapy for anxiety disorders.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] CBT appears to be equally effective when carried out via the internet compared to sessions completed face-to-face.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] There are specific CBT curriculums or strategies for the specific type of anxiety disorder.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] CBT has similar effectiveness to pharmacotherapy and in a meta analysis, CBT was associated with medium to large benefit effect sizes for GAD, panic disorder and social anxiety disorder.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] CBT has low dropout rates and its positive effects have been shown to be maintained at least for 12 months.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] CBT is sometimes given as once weekly sessions for 8–20 weeks, but regimens vary widely.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Booster sessions may need to be restarted for patients who have a relapse of symptoms.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Exposure and response prevention (ERP) has been found effective for treating OCD.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Mindfulness-based programs also appear to be effective for managing anxiety disorders.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] It is unclear if meditation has an effect on anxiety, and transcendental meditation appears to be no different from other types of meditation.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] A 2015 Cochrane review of Morita therapy for anxiety disorder in adults found insufficient evidence of an effect.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] First-line choices for medications include SSRIs or SNRIs to treat generalized anxiety disorder, social anxiety disorder or panic disorder.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] For adults, there is no good evidence supporting which specific medication in the SSRI or SNRI class is best for treating anxiety, so cost often drives drug choice.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Fluvoxamine is effective in treating a range of anxiety disorders in children and adolescents.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Fluoxetine, sertraline, and paroxetine can also help with some forms of anxiety in children and adolescents.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] If the chosen medicine is effective, it is recommended that it be continued for at least a year to mitigate the risk of a relapse.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Benzodiazepines are a second line option for the pharmacologic treatment of anxiety.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Benzodiazepines are associated with moderate to high effect sizes with regard to symptom relief and they have an onset usually within 1 week.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Clonazepam has a longer half life and may possibly be used as once per day dosing.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Benzodiazepines may also be used with SNRIs or SSRIs to initially reduce anxiety symptoms, and they may potentially be continued long term.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Benzodiazepines are not a first line pharmacologic treatment of anxiety disorders and they carry risks of physical dependence, psychological dependence, overdose death (especially when combined with opioids), misuse, cognitive impairment, falls and motor vehicle crashes.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Buspirone and pregabalin are second-line treatments for people who do not respond to SSRIs or SNRIs.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Pregabalin and gabapentin are effective in treating some anxiety disorders, but there is concern regarding their off-label use due to the lack of strong scientific evidence for their efficacy in multiple conditions and their proven side effects.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Medications need to be used with care among older adults, who are more likely to have side effects because of coexisting physical disorders.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Adherence problems are more likely among older people, who may have difficulty understanding, seeing, or remembering instructions.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] In general, medications are not seen as helpful for specific phobias, but benzodiazepines are sometimes used to help resolve acute episodes.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] In 2007, data were sparse for the efficacy of any drug.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Lifestyle changes include exercise, for which there is moderate evidence for some improvement, regularizing sleep patterns, reducing caffeine intake, and stopping smoking.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Stopping smoking has benefits for anxiety as great as or greater than those of medications.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] A meta-analysis found 2000 mg/day or more of omega-3 polyunsaturated fatty acids, such as fish oil, tended to reduce anxiety in placebo-controlled and uncontrolled studies, particularly in people with more significant symptoms.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] In 2026, a large meta-analysis published in the Lancet showed no effect on anxiety using cannabis.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Using cannabis to treat anxiety-related disorders can delay treatment with other, proven methods.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Both therapy and a number of medications have been found to be useful for treating childhood anxiety disorders.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Therapy is generally preferred to medication.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Cognitive behavioral therapy (CBT) is a good first-line therapy approach.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Studies have gathered substantial evidence for treatments that are not CBT-based as effective forms of treatment, expanding treatment options for those who do not respond to CBT.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Although studies have demonstrated the effectiveness of CBT for anxiety disorders in children and adolescents, evidence that it is more effective than treatment as usual, medication, or wait list controls is inconclusive.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Like adults, children may undergo psychotherapy, cognitive-behavioral therapy, or counseling.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Family therapy is a form of treatment in which the child meets with a therapist together with the primary guardians and siblings.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Each family member may attend individual therapy, but family therapy is typically a form of group therapy.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Art therapy is most commonly used when the child will not or cannot verbally communicate due to trauma or a disability in which they are nonverbal.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Participating in art activities allows the child to express what they otherwise may not be able to communicate to others.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] In play therapy, the child is allowed to play however they please as a therapist observes them.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] The therapist may intercede from time to time with a question, comment, or suggestion.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] This is often most effective when the family of the child plays a role in the treatment.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Globally, as of 2010, approximately 273 million (4.5% of the population) had an anxiety disorder.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] It is more common in females (5.2%) than males (2.8%).
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] In Europe, Africa, and Asia, lifetime rates of anxiety disorders are between 9 and 16%, and yearly rates are between 4 and 7%.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] In the United States, the lifetime prevalence of anxiety disorders is about 29%, and between 11 and 18% of adults have the condition in a given year.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] This difference is affected by the range of ways in which different cultures interpret anxiety symptoms and what they consider to be normative behavior.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] In general, anxiety disorders represent the most prevalent psychiatric condition in the United States, outside of substance use disorder.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Like adults, children can experience anxiety disorders; between 10 and 20 percent of all children will develop a full-fledged anxiety disorder prior to the age of 18, making anxiety the most common mental health issue in young people.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Anxiety disorders in children are often more challenging to identify than their adult counterparts, owing to the difficulty many parents face in discerning them from normal childhood fears.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Likewise, anxiety in children is sometimes misdiagnosed as attention deficit hyperactivity disorder, or, due to the tendency of children to interpret their emotions physically (as stomachaches, headaches, etc.), anxiety disorders may initially be confused with physical ailments.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Anxiety in children has a variety of causes; sometimes anxiety is rooted in biology and may be a product of another existing condition, such as autism spectrum disorder.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Gifted children are also often more prone to excessive anxiety than non-gifted children.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Other cases of anxiety arise from the child having experienced a traumatic event of some kind, and in some cases, the cause of the child's anxiety cannot be pinpointed.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Anxiety in children tends to manifest along age-appropriate themes, such as fear of going to school (not related to bullying) or not performing well enough at school, fear of social rejection, fear of something happening to loved ones, etc.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] What separates disordered anxiety from normal childhood anxiety is the duration and intensity of the fears involved.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] According to a 2011 study, people who rank highly in hypercompetitive traits are at increased risk of both anxiety and depression.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] People with an anxiety disorder may be challenged by prejudices and stereotypes held by other people, most likely as a result of misconceptions around anxiety and anxiety disorders.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Misconceptions found in a data analysis from the National Survey of Mental Health Literacy and Stigma include: (1) many people believe anxiety is not a real medical illness; and (2) many people believe that people with anxiety could turn it off if they wanted to.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] For people experiencing the physical and mental symptoms of an anxiety disorder, stigma and negative social perception can make an individual less likely to seek treatment.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Prejudice that some people with mental illness turn against themselves is called self-stigma.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] There is no explicit evidence for the exact cause of stigma towards anxiety.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Stigma can be divided by social scale, into the macro, intermediate, and micro levels.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] The macro-level marks society as a whole with the influence of mass media.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] The intermediate level includes healthcare professionals and their perspectives.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] The micro-level details the individual's contributions to the process through self-stigmatization.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] It has become very prevalent that many college students undergo some sort of mental disorder in their early adulthood.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Anxiety has become one of the main ones that has grown in prevalence over time.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] This is due to many issues such as different social pressures, school, career worries, etc.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] This has not only affected a lot of the youth in today's world but their overall quality of life.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] However, it is important to bring this issue to light since there is such a negative stigma when it comes to mental health; but rather than ignoring it and letting the issue grow exponentially larger, it is important to recognize ways that it can be lessened for future generations.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] Stigma can be described in three conceptual ways: cognitive, emotional, and behavioral.
[src:alistipes/anxiety-disorder] This allows for differentiation between stereotypes, prejudice, and discrimination.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] Generally, the basic morphologies are spheres (coccus) and round-ended cylinders or rod shaped (bacillus).
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] But, there are also other morphologies such as helically twisted cylinders (example *Spirochetes*), cylinders curved in one plane (selenomonads) and unusual morphologies (the square, flat box-shaped cells of the Archaean genus *Haloquadratum)*.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] Other arrangements include pairs, tetrads, clusters, chains and palisades.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] A **coccus** (plural *cocci*, from the Latin *coccinus* (scarlet) and derived from the Greek *kokkos* (berry)), is any microorganism (usually bacteria) whose overall shape is spherical or nearly spherical.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] Coccus refers to the shape of the bacteria and can contain multiple genera, such as staphylococci or streptococci.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] Cocci can grow in pairs, chains, or clusters, depending on their orientation and attachment during cell division.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] In contrast to many bacilli-shaped bacteria, most cocci bacteria do not have flagella and are non-motile.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] Cocci is an English loanword of a modern or Neo-Latin noun, which in turn stems from the Greek masculine noun κόκκος (*cóccos*) meaning 'berry'.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] Important human diseases caused by coccoid bacteria include staphylococcal infections, some types of food poisoning, some urinary tract infections, toxic shock syndrome, gonorrhea, as well as some forms of meningitis, throat infections, pneumonias, and sinusitis.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] The gram-positive cocci are a large group of bacteria with similar morphology.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] All are spherical or nearly so, but they vary considerably in size.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] Members of some genera are identifiable by the way cells are attached to one another: in pockets, in chains, or grape-like clusters.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] These arrangements reflect patterns of cell division and that cells stick together.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] *Sarcina* cells, for example, are arranged in cubical pockets because cell division alternates regularly among the three perpendicular planes.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] *Streptococcus* spp. resemble a string of beads because division always occurs in the same plane.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] Some of these strings, for example, *S. pneumoniae**,* are only two cells long.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] They are called *diplococci.* Species of *Staphylococcus* have no regular plane of division.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] The various gram-positive cocci differ physiologically and by habitat.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] *Micrococcus* spp. are obligate aerobes that inhabit human skin.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] *Staphylococcus* spp. also inhabit human skin, but they are facultative anaerobes.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] They ferment sugars, producing lactic acid as an end product.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] Many of these species produce carotenoid pigments, which color their colonies yellow or orange.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] *Staphylococcus aureus* is a major human pathogen.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] It can infect almost any tissue in the body, frequently the skin.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] It often causes nosocomial (hospital-acquired) infections.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] The genus *Moraxella* belongs to the family *Moraxellaceae*.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] However, only one has a morphology of diplococcus, *M. catarrhalis*, a salient pathogen contributing to infections in the human body.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] The species *Streptococcus pneumoniae* belongs to the genus *Streptococcus* and the family *Streptococcaceae*.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] The genus *Streptococcus* has around 129 species and 23 subspecies that benefit many microbiomes on the human body.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] There are many species that show non-pathogenic characteristics; however, there are some, like *S. pneumoniae*, that exhibit pathogenic characteristics in the human body.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] The genus *Enterococcus* belongs to the family *Enterococcaceae*.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] This genus is divided into 58 species and two subspecies.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] These gram-positive, coccoid bacteria were once thought to be harmless to the human body.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] However, within the last ten years, there has been an influx of nosocomial pathogens originating from *Enterococcus* bacteria.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] A **bacillus** (pl.: **bacilli**), also called a **bacilliform bacterium** or often just a **rod** (when the context makes the sense clear), is a rod-shaped bacterium or archaeon.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] Bacilli are found in many different taxonomic groups of bacteria.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] However, the name *Bacillus*, capitalized and italicized, refers to a specific genus of bacteria.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] The name Bacilli, capitalized but not italicized, can also refer to a less specific taxonomic group of bacteria that includes two orders, one of which contains the genus *Bacillus*.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] When the word is formatted with lowercase and not italicized, 'bacillus', it will most likely be referring to shape and not to the genus.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] Bacilliform bacteria are also often simply called rods when the bacteriologic context is clear.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] Bacilli usually divide in the same plane and are solitary, but can combine to form diplobacilli, streptobacilli, and palisades.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] There is no connection between the shape of a bacterium and its color upon Gram staining; there are both gram-positive rods and gram-negative rods.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] MacConkey agar can be used to distinguish among gram-negative bacilli such as *E. coli* and salmonella.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] A **coccobacillus** (plural **coccobacilli**), or **bacillococcus**, is a type of bacterium with a shape intermediate between cocci (spherical bacteria) and bacilli (rod-shaped bacteria).
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] Coccobacilli, then, are very short rods which may be mistaken for cocci.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] The word *coccobacillus* reflects an intermediate shape between *coccus* (spherical) and *bacillus* (elongated).
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] Bacteria are known to evolve specific traits to survive in their ideal environment.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] Bacteria-caused illnesses hinge on the bacteria's physiology and their ability to interact with their environment, including the ability to shapeshift.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] Researchers discovered a protein that allows the bacterium *Vibrio cholerae* to morph into a corkscrew shape that likely helps it twist into — and then escape — the protective mucus that lines the inside of the gut.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] A spirillum (plural spirilla) is a rigid spiral bacterium that is gram-negative and frequently has external amphitrichous or lophotrichous flagella.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] A spirochete (plural spirochetes) is a very thin, elongate, flexible, spiral bacteria that is motile via internal periplasmic flagella inside the outer membrane.
[src:alistipes/bacillus-shape] Owing to their morphological properties, spirochetes are difficult to Gram-stain but may be visualized using dark field microscopy or Warthin–Starry stain.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Like all animals, humans carry vast numbers (approximately 1013 to 1014) of bacteria.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Most are in the gut, though there are many on the skin.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Most of the bacteria in and on the body are harmless or rendered so by the protective effects of the immune system, and many are beneficial, particularly the ones in the gut.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] However, several species of bacteria are pathogenic and cause infectious diseases, including cholera, syphilis, anthrax, leprosy, tuberculosis, tetanus and bubonic plague.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The most common fatal bacterial diseases are respiratory infections.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Antibiotics are used to treat bacterial infections and are also used in farming, making antibiotic resistance a growing problem.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Once regarded as plants constituting the class *Schizomycetes* ("fission fungi"), bacteria are now classified as prokaryotes.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Unlike cells of animals and other eukaryotes, bacterial cells contain circular chromosomes, do not contain a nucleus and rarely harbour membrane-bound organelles.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Although the term *bacteria* traditionally included all prokaryotes, the scientific classification changed after the discovery in the 1990s that prokaryotes consist of two very different groups of organisms that evolved from an ancient common ancestor.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] These evolutionary domains are called Bacteria and Archaea.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Unlike Archaea, bacteria contain ester-linked lipids in the cell membrane, possess elongation factors that are resistant to ADP-ribosylation by diphtheria toxin, use formylmethionine in protein synthesis initiation, and have numerous genetic differences, including a different 16S rRNA.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The word was first used to refer to bacteria in 1828.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Although an estimated 43,000 species of bacteria have been named, most of them have never been studied.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] In fact, just 10 bacterial species account for half of all publications, whereas nearly 75% of all named bacteria have no academic research devoted to them.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The best-studied species, *Escherichia coli*, has more than 300,000 studies published on it, but many of these papers likely use it only as a cloning vehicle to study other species, without providing any insight into its own biology.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] 90% of scientific studies on bacteria focus on less than 1% of species, mostly pathogenic bacteria relevant to human health.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] While *E. coli* is probably the best-studied bacterium, a quarter of its 4000 genes are poorly studied or remain uncharacterized.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria with minimal genomes (< 600 genes, e.g.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] *Mycoplasma*) usually have a large fraction of their genes functionally characterized, given that most of them are essential and conserved in many other species.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The ancestors of bacteria were unicellular microorganisms that were the first forms of life to appear on Earth, about 4 billion years ago.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] For about 3 billion years, most organisms were microscopic, and bacteria and archaea were the dominant forms of life.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Although bacterial fossils exist, such as stromatolites, their lack of distinctive morphology prevents them from being used to examine the history of bacterial evolution, or to date the time of origin of a particular bacterial species.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] However, gene sequences can be used to reconstruct the bacterial phylogeny, and these studies indicate that bacteria diverged first from the archaeal/eukaryotic lineage.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The most recent common ancestor (MRCA) of bacteria and archaea was probably a hyperthermophile that lived about 2.5 billion–3.2 billion years ago.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The earliest life on land may have been bacteria some 3.22 billion years ago.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Bacteria were also involved in the second great evolutionary divergence, that of the archaea and eukaryotes.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Here, eukaryotes resulted from the entering of ancient bacteria into endosymbiotic associations with the ancestors of eukaryotic cells, which were themselves possibly related to the Archaea.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] This involved the engulfment by proto-eukaryotic cells of alphaproteobacterial symbionts to form either mitochondria or hydrogenosomes, which are still found in all known Eukarya (sometimes in highly reduced form, e.g. in species of amitochondrial protozoa).
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Later, some eukaryotes that already contained mitochondria also engulfed cyanobacteria-like organisms, leading to the formation of chloroplasts in algae and plants.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Bacteria are ubiquitous, living in every possible habitat on the planet including soil, underwater, deep in Earth's crust and even such extreme environments as acidic hot springs and radioactive waste.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] There are thought to be approximately 2×1030 bacteria on Earth, forming a biomass that is only exceeded by plants.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] They are abundant in lakes and oceans, in arctic ice, and geothermal springs where they provide the nutrients needed to sustain life by converting dissolved compounds, such as hydrogen sulphide and methane, to energy.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Most do not cause diseases, are beneficial to their environments, and are essential for life.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The soil is a rich source of bacteria and a few grams contain around a thousand million of them.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] They are all essential to soil ecology, breaking down toxic waste and recycling nutrients.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] They are even found in the atmosphere and one cubic metre of air holds around one hundred million bacterial cells.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The oceans and seas harbour around 3 × 1026 bacteria which provide up to 50% of the oxygen humans breathe.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Only around 2% of bacterial species have been fully studied.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Bacteria display a wide diversity of shapes and sizes.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Bacterial cells are about one-tenth the size of eukaryotic cells and are typically 0.5–5.0 micrometres in length.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] However, a few species are visible to the unaided eye—for example, *Thiomargarita namibiensis* is up to half a millimetre long, *Epulopiscium fishelsoni* reaches 0.7 mm, and *Thiomargarita magnifica* can reach even 2 cm in length, which is 50 times larger than other known bacteria.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Among the smallest bacteria are members of the genus *Mycoplasma*, which measure only 0.3 micrometres, as small as the largest viruses.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria may be even smaller, but these ultramicrobacteria are not well-studied.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Most bacterial species are either spherical, called *cocci* (*singular coccus*, from Greek *kókkos*, grain, seed), or rod-shaped, called *bacilli* (*sing*. bacillus, from Latin *baculus*, stick).
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria, called *vibrio*, are shaped like slightly curved rods or comma-shaped; others can be spiral-shaped, called *spirilla*, or tightly coiled, called *spirochaetes*.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] A small number of other unusual shapes have been described, such as star-shaped bacteria.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] This wide variety of shapes is determined by the bacterial cell wall and cytoskeleton and is important because it can influence the ability of bacteria to acquire nutrients, attach to surfaces, swim through liquids and escape predators.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Most bacterial species exist as single cells; others associate in characteristic patterns: *Neisseria* forms diploids (pairs), streptococci form chains, and staphylococci group together in "bunch of grapes" clusters.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Bacteria can also group to form larger multicellular structures, such as the elongated filaments of *Actinomycetota* species, the aggregates of *Myxobacteria* species, and the complex hyphae of *Streptomyces* species.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] These multicellular structures are often only seen in certain conditions.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] For example, when starved of amino acids, myxobacteria detect surrounding cells in a process known as quorum sensing, migrate towards each other, and aggregate to form fruiting bodies up to 500 micrometres long and containing approximately 100,000 bacterial cells.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] In these fruiting bodies, the bacteria perform separate tasks; for example, about one in ten cells migrate to the top of a fruiting body and differentiate into a specialised dormant state called a myxospore, which is more resistant to drying and other adverse environmental conditions.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Bacteria often attach to surfaces and form dense aggregations called biofilms and larger formations known as microbial mats.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] These biofilms and mats can range from a few micrometres in thickness to up to half a metre in depth, and may contain multiple species of bacteria, protists and archaea.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Bacteria living in biofilms display a complex arrangement of cells and extracellular components, forming secondary structures, such as microcolonies, through which there are networks of channels to enable better diffusion of nutrients.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] In natural environments, such as soil or the surfaces of plants, the majority of bacteria are bound to surfaces in biofilms.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Biofilms are also important in medicine, as these structures are often present during chronic bacterial infections or in infections of implanted medical devices, and bacteria protected within biofilms are much harder to kill than individual isolated bacteria.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The bacterial cell is surrounded by a cell membrane, which is made primarily of phospholipids.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] This membrane encloses the contents of the cell and acts as a barrier to hold nutrients, proteins and other essential components within the cell.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Unlike eukaryotic cells, bacteria usually lack large membrane-bound structures in their cytoplasm such as a nucleus, mitochondria, chloroplasts and the other organelles present in eukaryotic cells.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] However, some bacteria have protein-bound organelles in the cytoplasm which compartmentalise aspects of bacterial metabolism, such as the carboxysome.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Additionally, bacteria have a multi-component cytoskeleton to control the localisation of proteins and nucleic acids within the cell, and to manage the process of cell division.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Many important biochemical reactions, such as energy generation, occur due to differences in concentration of molecules across membranes, creating a electrochemical potential analogous to a battery.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The general lack of internal membranes in bacteria means these reactions, such as electron transport, occur across the cell membrane between the cytoplasm and the outside of the cell or periplasm.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] However, in many photosynthetic bacteria, the plasma membrane is highly folded and fills most of the cell with layers of light-gathering membrane.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] These light-gathering complexes may even form lipid-enclosed structures called chlorosomes in green sulfur bacteria.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Bacteria do not have a membrane-bound nucleus, and their genetic material is typically a single circular bacterial chromosome of DNA located in the cytoplasm in an irregularly shaped body called the nucleoid.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The nucleoid contains the chromosome with its associated proteins and RNA.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Like all other organisms, bacteria contain ribosomes for the production of proteins, but the structure of the bacterial ribosome is different from that of eukaryotes and archaea.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Its translation process is also different.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria produce intracellular nutrient storage granules, such as glycogen, polyphosphate, sulfur or polyhydroxyalkanoates.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Bacteria such as the photosynthetic cyanobacteria, produce internal gas vacuoles, which they use to regulate their buoyancy, allowing them to move up or down into water layers with different light intensities and nutrient levels.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Around the outside of the cell membrane is the cell wall.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Bacterial cell walls are made of peptidoglycan (also called murein), which is made from polysaccharide chains cross-linked by peptides containing D-amino acids.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Bacterial cell walls are different from the cell walls of plants and fungi, which are made of cellulose and chitin, respectively.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The cell wall of bacteria is also distinct from that of archaea, which do not contain peptidoglycan.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The cell wall is essential to the survival of many bacteria, and the antibiotic penicillin (produced by a fungus called *Penicillium*) is able to kill bacteria by inhibiting a step in the synthesis of peptidoglycan.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] There are broadly speaking two different types of cell wall in bacteria, that classify bacteria into Gram-positive bacteria and Gram-negative bacteria.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The names originate from the reaction of cells to the Gram stain, a long-standing test for the classification of bacterial species.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Gram-positive bacteria possess a thick cell wall containing many layers of peptidoglycan and teichoic acids.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] In contrast, Gram-negative bacteria have a relatively thin cell wall consisting of a few layers of peptidoglycan surrounded by a second lipid membrane containing lipopolysaccharides and lipoproteins.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Most bacteria have the Gram-negative cell wall, and only members of the *Bacillota* group and actinomycetota (previously known as the low G+C and high G+C Gram-positive bacteria, respectively) have the alternative Gram-positive arrangement.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] These differences in structure can produce differences in antibiotic susceptibility; for instance, vancomycin can kill only Gram-positive bacteria and is ineffective against Gram-negative pathogens, such as *Haemophilus influenzae* or *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria have cell wall structures that are neither classically Gram-positive or Gram-negative.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] This includes clinically important bacteria such as mycobacteria which have a thick peptidoglycan cell wall like a Gram-positive bacterium, but also a second outer layer of lipids.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] In many bacteria, an S-layer of rigidly arrayed protein molecules covers the outside of the cell.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] This layer provides chemical and physical protection for the cell surface and can act as a macromolecular diffusion barrier.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] S-layers have diverse functions and are known to act as virulence factors in *Campylobacter* species and contain surface enzymes in *Bacillus stearothermophilus*.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Flagella are rigid protein structures, about 20 nanometres in diameter and up to 20 micrometres in length, that are used for motility.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Flagella are driven by the energy released by the transfer of ions down an electrochemical gradient across the cell membrane.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Fimbriae (sometimes called "attachment pili") are fine filaments of protein, usually 2–10 nanometres in diameter and up to several micrometres in length.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] They are distributed over the surface of the cell, and resemble fine hairs when seen under the electron microscope.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Fimbriae are believed to be involved in attachment to solid surfaces or to other cells, and are essential for the virulence of some bacterial pathogens.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Pili (*sing*. pilus) are cellular appendages, slightly larger than fimbriae, that can transfer genetic material between bacterial cells in a process called conjugation where they are called conjugation pili or sex pili (see bacterial genetics, below).
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] They can also generate movement where they are called type IV pili.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Glycocalyx is produced by many bacteria to surround their cells, and varies in structural complexity: ranging from a disorganised slime layer of extracellular polymeric substances to a highly structured capsule.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] These structures can protect cells from engulfment by eukaryotic cells such as macrophages (part of the human immune system).
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] They can also act as antigens and be involved in cell recognition, as well as aiding attachment to surfaces and the formation of biofilms.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The assembly of these extracellular structures is dependent on bacterial secretion systems.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] These transfer proteins from the cytoplasm into the periplasm or into the environment around the cell.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Many types of secretion systems are known and these structures are often essential for the virulence of pathogens, so are intensively studied.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Some genera of Gram-positive bacteria, such as *Bacillus*, *Clostridium*, *Sporohalobacter*, *Anaerobacter*, and *Heliobacterium*, can form highly resistant, dormant structures called *endospores*.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Endospores develop within the cytoplasm of the cell; generally, a single endospore develops in each cell.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Each endospore contains a core of DNA and ribosomes surrounded by a cortex layer and protected by a multilayer rigid coat composed of peptidoglycan and a variety of proteins.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Endospores show no detectable metabolism and can survive extreme physical and chemical stresses, such as high levels of UV light, gamma radiation, detergents, disinfectants, heat, freezing, pressure, and desiccation.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] In this dormant state, these organisms may remain viable for millions of years.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Endospores even allow bacteria to survive exposure to the vacuum and radiation of outer space, leading to the possibility that bacteria could be distributed throughout the universe by space dust, meteoroids, asteroids, comets, planetoids, or directed panspermia.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] *Clostridioides difficile* infection, a common problem in healthcare settings, is caused by spore-forming bacteria.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Bacteria exhibit an extremely wide variety of metabolic types.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The distribution of metabolic traits within a group of bacteria has traditionally been used to define their taxonomy, but these traits often do not correspond with modern genetic classifications.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Bacterial metabolism is classified into nutritional groups on the basis of three major criteria: the source of energy, the electron donors used, and the source of carbon used for growth.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Phototrophic bacteria derive energy from light using photosynthesis, while chemotrophic bacteria breaking down chemical compounds through oxidation, driving metabolism by transferring electrons from a given electron donor to a terminal electron acceptor in a redox reaction.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Chemotrophs are further divided by the types of compounds they use to transfer electrons.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Bacteria that derive electrons from inorganic compounds such as hydrogen, carbon monoxide, or ammonia are called lithotrophs, while those that use organic compounds are called organotrophs.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Still, more specifically, aerobic organisms use oxygen as the terminal electron acceptor, while anaerobic organisms use other compounds such as nitrate, sulfate, or carbon dioxide.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Many bacteria, called heterotrophs, derive their carbon from other organic carbon.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Others, such as cyanobacteria and some purple bacteria, are autotrophic, meaning they obtain cellular carbon by fixing carbon dioxide.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] In unusual circumstances, the gas methane can be used by methanotrophic bacteria as both a source of electrons and a substrate for carbon anabolism.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] In many ways, bacterial metabolism provides traits that are useful for ecological stability and for human society.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] For example, diazotrophs have the ability to fix nitrogen gas using the enzyme nitrogenase.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] This trait, which can be found in bacteria of most metabolic types listed above, leads to the ecologically important processes of denitrification, sulfate reduction, and acetogenesis, respectively.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Bacterial metabolic processes are important drivers in biological responses to pollution; for example, sulfate-reducing bacteria are largely responsible for the production of the highly toxic forms of mercury (methyl- and dimethylmercury) in the environment.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Nonrespiratory anaerobes use fermentation to generate energy and reducing power, secreting metabolic by-products (such as ethanol in brewing) as waste.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Facultative anaerobes can switch between fermentation and different terminal electron acceptors depending on the environmental conditions in which they find themselves.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Unlike in multicellular organisms, increases in cell size (cell growth) and reproduction by cell division are tightly linked in unicellular organisms.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Bacteria grow to a fixed size and then reproduce through binary fission, a form of asexual reproduction.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Under optimal conditions, bacteria can grow and divide extremely rapidly, and some bacterial populations can double as quickly as every 17 minutes.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] In cell division, two identical clone daughter cells are produced.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria, while still reproducing asexually, form more complex reproductive structures that help disperse the newly formed daughter cells.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Examples include fruiting body formation by myxobacteria and aerial hyphae formation by *Streptomyces* species, or budding.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Budding involves a cell forming a protrusion that breaks away and produces a daughter cell.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] In the laboratory, bacteria are usually grown using solid or liquid media.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Solid growth media, such as agar plates, are used to isolate pure cultures of a bacterial strain.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] However, liquid growth media are used when the measurement of growth or large volumes of cells are required.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Growth in stirred liquid media occurs as an even cell suspension, making the cultures easy to divide and transfer, although isolating single bacteria from liquid media is difficult.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The use of selective media (media with specific nutrients added or deficient, or with antibiotics added) can help identify specific organisms.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Most laboratory techniques for growing bacteria use high levels of nutrients to produce large amounts of cells cheaply and quickly.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] However, in natural environments, nutrients are limited, meaning that bacteria cannot continue to reproduce indefinitely.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] This nutrient limitation has led the evolution of different growth strategies (see r/K selection theory).
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Some organisms can grow extremely rapidly when nutrients become available, such as the formation of algal and cyanobacterial blooms that often occur in lakes during the summer.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Other organisms have adaptations to harsh environments, such as the production of multiple antibiotics by *Streptomyces* that inhibit the growth of competing microorganisms.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] In nature, many organisms live in communities (e.g., biofilms) that may allow for increased supply of nutrients and protection from environmental stresses.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] These relationships can be essential for growth of a particular organism or group of organisms (syntrophy).
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] When a population of bacteria first enter a high-nutrient environment that allows growth, the cells need to adapt to their new environment.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The first phase of growth is the lag phase, a period of slow growth when the cells are adapting to the high-nutrient environment and preparing for fast growth.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The lag phase has high biosynthesis rates, as proteins necessary for rapid growth are produced.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The second phase of growth is the logarithmic phase, also known as the exponential phase.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The log phase is marked by rapid exponential growth.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The rate at which cells grow during this phase is known as the *growth rate* (*k*), and the time it takes the cells to double is known as the *generation time* (*g*).
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] During log phase, nutrients are metabolised at maximum speed until one of the nutrients is depleted and starts limiting growth.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The third phase of growth is the *stationary phase* and is caused by depleted nutrients.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The cells reduce their metabolic activity and consume non-essential cellular proteins.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The stationary phase is a transition from rapid growth to a stress response state and there is increased expression of genes involved in DNA repair, antioxidant metabolism and nutrient transport.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The final phase is the death phase where the bacteria run out of nutrients and die.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] There are many exceptions to this; for example, some *Streptomyces* and *Borrelia* species contain a single linear chromosome, while some bacteria including species of *Vibrio* contain more than one chromosome.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria contain plasmids, small extra-chromosomal molecules of DNA that may contain genes for various useful functions such as antibiotic resistance, metabolic capabilities, or various virulence factors.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Whether they have a single chromosome or more than one, almost all bacteria have a haploid genome.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] This means that they have only one copy of each gene encoding proteins.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] This is in contrast to eukaryotes, which are diploid or polyploid, meaning they have two or more copies of each gene.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] This means that unlike humans, who may still be able to create a protein if the gene becomes mutated (since the human genome has an extra copy in each cell), a bacterium will be completely unable to create the protein if its gene incurs an inactivating mutation.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Bacterial genomes usually encode a few hundred to a few thousand genes.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The genes in bacterial genomes are usually a single continuous stretch of DNA.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Although several different types of introns do exist in bacteria, these are much rarer than in eukaryotes.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Bacteria, as asexual organisms, inherit an identical copy of the parent's genome and are clonal.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] However, all bacteria can evolve by selection on changes to their genetic material DNA caused by genetic recombination or mutations.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Mutations arise from errors made during the replication of DNA or from exposure to mutagens.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Mutation rates vary widely among different species of bacteria and even among different clones of a single species of bacteria.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Genetic changes in bacterial genomes emerge from either random mutation during replication or "stress-directed mutation", where genes involved in a particular growth-limiting process have an increased mutation rate.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria transfer genetic material between cells.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] First, bacteria can take up exogenous DNA from their environment in a process called transformation.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Many bacteria can naturally take up DNA from the environment, while others must be chemically altered in order to induce them to take up DNA.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The development of competence in nature is usually associated with stressful environmental conditions and seems to be an adaptation for facilitating repair of DNA damage in recipient cells.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Second, bacteriophages can integrate into the bacterial chromosome, introducing foreign DNA in a process known as transduction.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Many types of bacteriophage exist; some infect and lyse their host bacteria, while others insert into the bacterial chromosome.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Third, bacteria can transfer genetic material through direct cell contact via conjugation.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] In such cases, gene acquisition from other bacteria or the environment is called horizontal gene transfer and may be common under natural conditions.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Many bacteria are motile (able to move themselves) and do so using a variety of mechanisms.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The best studied of these are flagella, long filaments that are turned by a motor at the base to generate propeller-like movement.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The bacterial flagellum is made of about 20 proteins, with approximately another 30 proteins required for its regulation and assembly.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The flagellum is a rotating structure driven by a reversible motor at the base that uses the electrochemical gradient across the membrane for power.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Bacteria can use flagella in different ways to generate different kinds of movement.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Many bacteria (such as *E. coli*) have two distinct modes of movement: forward movement (swimming) and tumbling.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The tumbling allows them to reorient and makes their movement a three-dimensional random walk.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The flagella of a group of bacteria, the spirochaetes, are found between two membranes in the periplasmic space.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] They have a distinctive helical body that twists about as it moves.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Two other types of bacterial motion are called twitching motility that relies on a structure called the type IV pilus, and gliding motility, that uses other mechanisms.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] In twitching motility, the rod-like pilus extends out from the cell, binds some substrate, and then retracts, pulling the cell forward.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Motile bacteria are attracted or repelled by certain stimuli in behaviours called *taxes*: these include chemotaxis, phototaxis, energy taxis, and magnetotaxis.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] In one peculiar group, the myxobacteria, individual bacteria move together to form waves of cells that then differentiate to form fruiting bodies containing spores.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The myxobacteria move only when on solid surfaces, unlike *E. coli*, which is motile in liquid or solid media.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Several *Listeria* and *Shigella* species move inside host cells by usurping the cytoskeleton, which is normally used to move organelles inside the cell.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] By promoting actin polymerisation at one pole of their cells, they can form a kind of tail that pushes them through the host cell's cytoplasm.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] A few bacteria have chemical systems that generate light.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] This bioluminescence often occurs in bacteria that live in association with fish, and the light probably serves to attract fish or other large animals.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Bacteria often function as multicellular aggregates known as biofilms, exchanging a variety of molecular signals for intercell communication and engaging in coordinated multicellular behaviour.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The communal benefits of multicellular cooperation include a cellular division of labour, accessing resources that cannot effectively be used by single cells, collectively defending against antagonists, and optimising population survival by differentiating into distinct cell types.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] For example, bacteria in biofilms can have more than five hundred times the increased resistance to antibacterial agents than individual "planktonic" bacteria of the same species.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] One type of intercellular communication by a molecular signal is called quorum sensing.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Quorum sensing determines whether the local population is dense enough to support investment in processes that are only successful if large numbers of similar organisms behave similarly, such as excreting digestive enzymes or emitting light.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Quorum sensing enables bacteria to coordinate gene expression and to produce, release, and detect autoinducers or pheromones that accumulate with the growth in cell population.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Classification seeks to describe the diversity of bacterial species by naming and grouping organisms based on similarities.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Bacteria can be classified on the basis of cell structure, cellular metabolism or on differences in cell components, such as DNA, fatty acids, pigments, antigens and quinones.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] While these schemes allowed the identification and classification of **bacterial strains**, it was unclear whether these differences represented variation between distinct species or between strains of the same species.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] This uncertainty was due to the lack of distinctive structures in most bacteria, as well as lateral gene transfer between unrelated species.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Due to lateral gene transfer, some closely related bacteria can have very different morphologies and metabolisms.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Classification of bacteria is determined by publication in the International Journal of Systematic Bacteriology, and Bergey's Manual of Systematic Bacteriology.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The International Committee on Systematic Bacteriology (ICSB) maintains international rules for the naming of bacteria and taxonomic categories and for the ranking of them in the International Code of Nomenclature of Bacteria.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Historically, bacteria were considered a part of the Plantae, the plant kingdom, and were called "Schizomycetes" (fission-fungi).
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] For this reason, collective bacteria and other microorganisms in a host are often called "flora".
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The term "bacteria" was traditionally applied to all microscopic, single-cell prokaryotes.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] However, molecular systematics showed prokaryotic life to consist of two separate domains, originally called Eubacteria and Archaebacteria, but now called Bacteria and Archaea that evolved independently from an ancient common ancestor.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The archaea and eukaryotes are more closely related to each other than either is to the bacteria.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] These two domains, along with Eukarya, are the basis of the three-domain system, which is currently the most widely used classification system in microbiology.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] However, due to the relatively recent introduction of molecular systematics and a rapid increase in the number of genome sequences that are available, bacterial classification remains a changing and expanding field.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] For example, Cavalier-Smith argued that the Archaea and Eukaryotes evolved from Gram-positive bacteria.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The identification of bacteria in the laboratory is particularly relevant in medicine, where the correct treatment is determined by the bacterial species causing an infection.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Consequently, the need to identify human pathogens was a major impetus for the development of techniques to identify bacteria.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Once a pathogenic organism has been isolated, it can be further characterised by its morphology, growth patterns (such as aerobic or anaerobic growth), patterns of hemolysis, and staining.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The *Gram stain*, developed in 1884 by Hans Christian Gram, characterises bacteria based on the structural characteristics of their cell walls.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The thick layers of peptidoglycan in the "Gram-positive" cell wall stain purple, while the thin "Gram-negative" cell wall appears pink.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] By combining morphology and Gram-staining, most bacteria can be classified as belonging to one of four groups (Gram-positive cocci, Gram-positive bacilli, Gram-negative cocci and Gram-negative bacilli).
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Some organisms are best identified by stains other than the Gram stain, particularly mycobacteria or *Nocardia*, which show acid fastness on Ziehl–Neelsen or similar stains.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Culture techniques are designed to promote the growth and identify particular bacteria while restricting the growth of the other bacteria in the sample.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Often these techniques are designed for specific specimens; for example, a sputum sample will be treated to identify organisms that cause pneumonia, while stool specimens are cultured on selective media to identify organisms that cause diarrhea while preventing growth of non-pathogenic bacteria.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Specimens that are normally sterile, such as blood, urine or spinal fluid, are cultured under conditions designed to grow all possible organisms.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Other organisms may need to be identified by their growth in special media, or by other techniques, such as serology.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] As with bacterial classification, identification of bacteria is increasingly using molecular methods, and mass spectroscopy.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Most bacteria have not been characterised and there are many species that cannot be grown in the laboratory.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Diagnostics using DNA-based tools, such as polymerase chain reaction, are increasingly popular due to their specificity and speed, compared to culture-based methods.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] These methods also allow the detection and identification of "viable but nonculturable" cells that are metabolically active but non-dividing.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] The main way to characterize and classify these bacteria is to isolate their DNA from environmental samples and mass-sequence them.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] This approach has identified thousands, if not millions of candidate species.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p01] Based on some estimates, more than 43,000 species of bacteria have been described, but attempts to estimate the true number of bacterial diversity have ranged from 107 to 109 total species—and even these diverse estimates may be off by many orders of magnitude.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Despite their apparent simplicity, bacteria can form complex associations with other organisms.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] These symbiotic associations can be divided into parasitism, mutualism and commensalism.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] The word "commensalism" is derived from the word "commensal", meaning "eating at the same table" and all plants and animals are colonised by commensal bacteria.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] In humans and other animals, trillions of them live on the skin, the airways, the gut and other orifices.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Referred to as "normal flora", or "commensals", these bacteria usually cause no harm but may occasionally invade other sites of the body and cause infection.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] *Escherichia coli* is a commensal in the human gut but can cause urinary tract infections.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Similarly, streptococci, which are part of the normal flora of the human mouth, can cause heart disease.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Some species of bacteria kill and then consume other microorganisms; these species are called *predatory bacteria*.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] These include organisms such as *Myxococcus xanthus*, which forms swarms of cells that kill and digest any bacteria they encounter.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Other bacterial predators either attach to their prey in order to digest them and absorb nutrients or invade another cell and multiply inside the cytosol.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] These predatory bacteria are thought to have evolved from saprophages that consumed dead microorganisms, through adaptations that allowed them to entrap and kill other organisms.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Certain bacteria form close spatial associations that are essential for their survival.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] One such mutualistic association, called interspecies hydrogen transfer, occurs between clusters of anaerobic bacteria that consume organic acids, such as butyric acid or propionic acid, and produce hydrogen, and methanogenic archaea that consume hydrogen.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] The bacteria in this association are unable to consume the organic acids as this reaction produces hydrogen that accumulates in their surroundings.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Only the intimate association with the hydrogen-consuming archaea keeps the hydrogen concentration low enough to allow the bacteria to grow.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] In soil, microorganisms that reside in the rhizosphere (a zone that includes the root surface and the soil that adheres to the root after gentle shaking) carry out nitrogen fixation, converting nitrogen gas to nitrogenous compounds.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] This serves to provide an easily absorbable form of nitrogen for many plants, which cannot fix nitrogen themselves.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Many other bacteria are found as symbionts in humans and other organisms.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] The presence of this gut flora also inhibits the growth of potentially pathogenic bacteria (usually through competitive exclusion) and these beneficial bacteria are consequently sold as probiotic dietary supplements.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Nearly all animal life is dependent on bacteria for survival as only bacteria and some archaea possess the genes and enzymes necessary to synthesise vitamin B12, also known as cobalamin, and provide it through the food chain.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Vitamin B12 is a water-soluble vitamin that is involved in the metabolism of every cell of the human body.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] It is a cofactor in DNA synthesis and in both fatty acid and amino acid metabolism.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] It is particularly important in the normal functioning of the nervous system via its role in the synthesis of myelin.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] The body is continually exposed to many species of bacteria, including beneficial commensals, which grow on the skin and mucous membranes, and saprophytes, which grow mainly in the soil and in decaying matter.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] The blood and tissue fluids contain nutrients sufficient to sustain the growth of many bacteria.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] The body has defence mechanisms that enable it to resist microbial invasion of its tissues and give it a natural immunity or innate resistance against many microorganisms.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Unlike some viruses, bacteria evolve relatively slowly so many bacterial diseases also occur in other animals.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] If bacteria form a parasitic association with other organisms, they are classed as pathogens.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] A pathogenic cause for a known medical disease may only be discovered many years later, as was the case with *Helicobacter pylori* and peptic ulcer disease.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Bacterial diseases are also important in agriculture, and bacteria cause leaf spot, fire blight and wilts in plants, as well as Johne's disease, mastitis, salmonella and anthrax in farm animals.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Each species of pathogen has a characteristic spectrum of interactions with its human hosts.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Some organisms, such as *Staphylococcus* or *Streptococcus*, can cause skin infections, pneumonia, meningitis and sepsis, a systemic inflammatory response producing shock, massive vasodilation and death.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Yet these organisms are also part of the normal human flora and usually exist on the skin or in the nose without causing any disease at all.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Other organisms invariably cause disease in humans, such as *Rickettsia*, which are obligate intracellular parasites able to grow and reproduce only within the cells of other organisms.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] One species of *Rickettsia* causes typhus, while another causes Rocky Mountain spotted fever.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] *Chlamydia*, another phylum of obligate intracellular parasites, contains species that can cause pneumonia or urinary tract infection and may be involved in coronary heart disease.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Some species, such as *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*, *Burkholderia cenocepacia*, and *Mycobacterium avium*, are opportunistic pathogens and cause disease mainly in people who are immunosuppressed or have cystic fibrosis.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Some bacteria produce toxins, which cause diseases.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] These are endotoxins, which come from broken bacterial cells, and exotoxins, which are produced by bacteria and released into the environment.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] The bacterium *Clostridium botulinum* for example, produces a powerful exotoxin that cause respiratory paralysis, and *Salmonellae* produce an endotoxin that causes gastroenteritis.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Some exotoxins can be converted to toxoids, which are used as vaccines to prevent the disease.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Bacterial infections may be treated with antibiotics, which are classified as bacteriocidal if they kill bacteria or bacteriostatic if they just prevent bacterial growth.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] There are many types of antibiotics, and each class inhibits a process that is different in the pathogen from that found in the host.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] An example of how antibiotics produce selective toxicity are chloramphenicol and puromycin, which inhibit the bacterial ribosome, but not the structurally different eukaryotic ribosome.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Antibiotics are used both in treating human disease and in intensive farming to promote animal growth, where they may be contributing to the rapid development of antibiotic resistance in bacterial populations.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Infections can be prevented by antiseptic measures such as sterilising the skin prior to piercing it with the needle of a syringe, and by proper care of indwelling catheters.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Surgical and dental instruments are also sterilised to prevent contamination by bacteria.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Disinfectants such as bleach are used to kill bacteria or other pathogens on surfaces to prevent contamination and further reduce the risk of infection.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Bacteria, often lactic acid bacteria, such as *Lactobacillus* species and *Lactococcus* species, in combination with yeasts and moulds, have been used for thousands of years in the preparation of fermented foods, such as cheese, pickles, soy sauce, sauerkraut, vinegar, wine, and yogurt.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] The ability of bacteria to degrade a variety of organic compounds is remarkable and has been used in waste processing and bioremediation.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Bacteria capable of digesting the hydrocarbons in petroleum are often used to clean up oil spills.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Fertiliser was added to some of the beaches in Prince William Sound in an attempt to promote the growth of these naturally occurring bacteria after the 1989 *Exxon Valdez* oil spill.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] These efforts were effective on beaches that were not too thickly covered in oil.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Bacteria are also used for the bioremediation of industrial toxic wastes.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] In the chemical industry, bacteria are most important in the production of enantiomerically pure chemicals for use as pharmaceuticals or agrichemicals.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Bacteria can also be used in place of pesticides in biological pest control.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] This commonly involves *Bacillus thuringiensis* (also called BT), a Gram-positive, soil-dwelling bacterium.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Subspecies of this bacteria are used as Lepidopteran-specific insecticides under trade names such as Dipel and Thuricide.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Because of their specificity, these pesticides are regarded as environmentally friendly, with little or no effect on humans, wildlife, pollinators, and most other beneficial insects.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Because of their ability to quickly grow and the relative ease with which they can be manipulated, bacteria are the workhorses for the fields of molecular biology, genetics, and biochemistry.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] By making mutations in bacterial DNA and examining the resulting phenotypes, scientists can determine the function of genes, enzymes, and metabolic pathways in bacteria, then apply this knowledge to more complex organisms.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] This aim of understanding the biochemistry of a cell reaches its most complex expression in the synthesis of huge amounts of enzyme kinetic and gene expression data into mathematical models of entire organisms.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] This is achievable in some well-studied bacteria, with models of *Escherichia coli* metabolism now being produced and tested.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] This understanding of bacterial metabolism and genetics allows the use of biotechnology to bioengineer bacteria for the production of therapeutic proteins, such as insulin, growth factors, or antibodies.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Because of their importance for research in general, samples of bacterial strains are isolated and preserved in Biological Resource Centres.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] This ensures the availability of the strain to scientists worldwide.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Bacteria were first observed by the Dutch microscopist Antonie van Leeuwenhoek in 1676, using a single-lens microscope of his own design.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Leeuwenhoek did not recognize bacteria as a distinct category of microorganisms, referring to all microorganisms that he observed, including bacteria, protists, and microscopic animals, as animalcules.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] He published his observations in a series of letters to the Royal Society of London.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Bacteria were Leeuwenhoek's most remarkable microscopic discovery.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Their size was just at the limit of what his simple lenses could resolve, and, in one of the most striking hiatuses in the history of science, no one else would see them again for over a century.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] His observations also included protozoans, and his findings were looked at again in the light of the more recent findings of cell theory.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Christian Gottfried Ehrenberg introduced the word "bacterium" in 1828.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] In fact, his *Bacterium* was a genus that contained non-spore-forming rod-shaped bacteria, as opposed to *Bacillus*, a genus of spore-forming rod-shaped bacteria defined by Ehrenberg in 1835.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Louis Pasteur demonstrated in 1859 that the growth of microorganisms causes the fermentation process and that this growth is not due to spontaneous generation (yeasts and molds, commonly associated with fermentation, are not bacteria, but rather fungi).
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Along with his contemporary Robert Koch, Pasteur was an early advocate of the germ theory of disease.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Before them, Ignaz Semmelweis and Joseph Lister had realised the importance of sanitised hands in medical work.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Semmelweis, who in the 1840s formulated his rules for handwashing in the hospital, prior to the advent of germ theory, attributed disease to "decomposing animal organic matter".
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] His ideas were rejected and his book on the topic condemned by the medical community.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] After Lister, however, doctors started sanitising their hands in the 1870s.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Robert Koch, a pioneer in medical microbiology, worked on cholera, anthrax and tuberculosis.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] In his research into tuberculosis, Koch finally proved the germ theory, for which he received a Nobel Prize in 1905.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] In Koch's postulates, he set out criteria to test if an organism is the cause of a disease, and these postulates are still used today.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Ferdinand Cohn is said to be a founder of bacteriology, studying bacteria from 1870.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Cohn was the first to classify bacteria based on their morphology.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Though it was known in the nineteenth century that bacteria are the cause of many diseases, no effective antibacterial treatments were available.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] In 1910, Paul Ehrlich developed the first antibiotic, by changing dyes that selectively stained *Treponema pallidum*—the spirochaete that causes syphilis—into compounds that selectively killed the pathogen.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] Ehrlich, who had been awarded a 1908 Nobel Prize for his work on immunology, pioneered the use of stains to detect and identify bacteria, with his work being the basis of the Gram stain and the Ziehl–Neelsen stain.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] A major step forward in the study of bacteria came in 1977 when Carl Woese recognised that archaea have a separate line of evolutionary descent from bacteria.
[src:alistipes/bacteria-p02] This new phylogenetic taxonomy depended on the sequencing of 16S ribosomal RNA and divided prokaryotes into two evolutionary domains, as part of the three-domain system.
